--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Most Sullon players, I think, noticed the MOTD on Sullon last week hinting that the Nameless was thinking of levying large penalties against those in the Evil Alliance due to the outnumbering of others. Frankly, we're wondering if anything *really* needs to be done. <br>
Evils currently outnumber good and neutral combined and have a higher average level due to there being safety in numbers and the geographical isolation of the Iksar. <br>
<br>
So why did so many people join Evil? It's not one of power -- The class availability of the teams is in good balance. I imagine zone-control is a big part, but my guess is that it comes down mostly to &quot;evil&quot; seeming &quot;cooler&quot; than good. Do players *really* find this a problem? How many players joined Good expressly for the higher difficulty level and the &quot;target rich environment&quot;? How many joined evil due to a desire to be a part of what's imagined to be the &quot;winning team&quot;?<br>
<br>
Right now based on the point-system announced last week, evil and good are scoring a similar number of points despite there being 4x as many evils as good. Neutral on the other hand is laying waste to both other teams despite being outnumbered by evil?<br>
<br>
I suppose what it comes down to more than anything is: Are people having fun? <br>
<br>
We have been discussing potential &quot;solutions&quot; to the team lop-sidedness. Some have suggested that we tweak experience rewards so that Good and Neutral level faster in order to make those teams more attractive. Others have suggested that we make evil level slower. Differing experience penalties on death have also been discussed. Frankly I'm not a fan of either of these ideas for one main reason: Everyone caps out at level 60, and come level 60 differing experience requirements don't mean squat.<br>
<br>
There is another idea that we've been discussing. It's passed internal muster, which means it's time to bring it up and see what Sullon players think. As it's hard for us to query players of individual servers or rulesets on their thought, I'll ask everyone replying to open their reply with whether or not they play on Sullon currently.<br>
<br>
Our idea is this, in the words of EQLive's Assistant Producer Bill &quot;Solist&quot; Coyle, what's the one thing throughout fantasy literature that has made it possible for Good to stand their ground and beat back the overwhelming forces of Evil? <br>
<br>
<br>
/em plays some suspenseful music...<br>
<br>
<br>
.<br>
<br>
<br>
.<br>
<br>
<br>
.<br>
<br>
<br>
.<br>
<br>
<br>
Wait for it....<br>
<br>
.<br>
<br>
<br>
.<br>
<br>
<br>
.<br>
<br>
.<br>
<br>
Why, it's the fact that Evil eventually turns on itself. <br>
<br>
Duh duh duh duuuuuum!<br>
<br>
Our idea is, simply, allow Team Evil to attack each other... <br>
<br>
Thoughts?<br>
<br>
